I inherited this shotgun a couple years ago, took it to Wade's in Bellevue, WA for a clean and inspection prior to firing. The gun itself is the value version of the Savage .410, the only difference being the material used for the stock and finish. While this article is supposed to cover widely available surplus firearms, I couldn’t help including the M1 Carbine. It’s one of the only historic U.S. military firearms still somewhat available, and because there’s really nothing else quite like it.

It was initially developed to be a lighter, more maneuverable rifle than the standard service M1 Garand, with more power and precision than the 1911 and M1917 handguns. It first served in the European Theater in the hands of various branches of the military, most notably among paratroopers, forward artillery observers, officers and ammunition bearers. Later, in a select-fire version fitted with an infrared scope, dubbed the “T3” variation, it did yeoman’s duty at night during the Okinawan campaign. Select-fire M2s were heavily deployed during the Korean War, where they gained a reputation for jamming and had inadequate stopping power in extreme cold.

title: For Sale:  Mauser Model P38 "Gray Ghost" Pistol (9mm)
postcontent:
Up for sale is a unique piece of history, It is a Mauser “Gray Ghost” P38 Pistol (9mm). This units D.O.M. Is 1944 made by the French under German occupation during WW II. The term “Gray Ghost” came from the Gray phosphate finish and metal grips so commonly applied to these particular pistols. Very little if any of the original finish remains on this pistol, there seems to be pitting & fouling in the grooves of the bore but the lands are still strong and shiny. The magazine that accompanies this pistol is correct (according to the research we have been able to do). Overall this pistol is in great shape considering its age and would make a fine addition to a gun collection of pieces from that era.
